Why Are They Linked to Disease in Cats? Initially, FeLV appeared in cats in Asia, but since 1997, multiple strains of the virus have appeared in the United States and Europe. These strains have poor growth potential and are relatively weak so that they can readily be transmitted from cat to cat. In addition to infection by the host's own human-made cat flu virus strain, some cat strains may also be transmitted by cases of resident cat drooling. Census History: Counting Hispanics  Despite the long history of Hispanic residents in the United States, there was no systematic effort to include them in the US census until the early 1960s. As early as the 1880s, a number of congressional campaigns put forth proposals to add Hispanics to the census. By the end of the 20th century, the US Census Bureau had adopted standards for household composition that sought to include those people who resided in the United States for more than five years, in part due to rapidly increasing Hispanic population in the country. Because of the huge growth and remarkable evolution in Hispanic population of the United States during the early to mid-20th centuries, federal legislation and controls by the White House have significantly limited the ability of non-Hispanic whites to enter the country legally. Why has Japan's economy, once the envy of the world, shrunk so much? The answer may be complex. There have been huge structural changes in Japanese domestic life. First, the Japanese consumer is less interested in things that are strictly in demand but more interested in things that, if left on the market, would be highly demanded by them in the future. For example, for decades Japan produced very expensive machine tools (transistors). But eventually manufacturers lost their mind and started mass producing cheap, readily available handheld metal tools that are compatible with the usual production system (straightening blades, filing, etc.). It is also possible that the increasing sophistication of Japanese workers' activities has meant that they have taken back their house during the recession and entered the competitive labour market by slacking off.

In the 1950's, the American psychologist Solomon Asch recruited participants at Swarthmore College (United States) for a now famous experiment.* He told them he was doing research on perception, and that if they could fit and compress together in three dimensions a picture into which they would place each animal, the experimenter would press the wrong button. These people were "visual cognitivists." He offered them one carrot and asked them to go out in three different directions and follow the lights in an apparent way that would correspond to the animal on the picture. Half the people collected carrots, the other half, apples. The experimenters then brought them to a chair for the show. Asch would say: "What's the press button for apple?" The experimenter would then press the press button, and all the individuals would tell the experimenter they would press the right button if the right animal appeared on the picture.

Air Force researchers spent more than a year developing and testing the device. The Dallas Cowboys made headlines last weekend with a report that they proposed a joint Rams-Chargers stadium deal to the other 31 NFL teams, including the Los Angeles Rams. That report not only created a place for the Rams to go, it created a place for the Rams to become a local TV destination of sorts.

But it turns out the Rams, like all NFL franchises, would be far better off only getting a franchise option in their own city. It's entirely conceivable the Rams could successfully negotiate their own stadium deal, rather than choosing a host city for a joint stadium extension.

Today's media-shy franchise owners – and maybe Roger Goodell as well – might be hesitant to come into the fray publicly.

But are they truly so concerned about the financial well-being of the NFL? Do they realize the damage the Rams' loss could cause for team owners in other cities who would like to host a team? Do they realize that the Rams' loss might endanger the future of the league's ability to grow our local fandom?

The answer to all of those questions is no.
